<chapter xml:id="chapter-substitution" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Reversing the Chain Rule</title>

<section xml:id="section-substitution">
<title>Integrating a derivative</title>

<!--   FIRST GO ... TOO COMPLICATED

<p>
<xref ref="theorem-fund-thm" text="title" />
says that if we create an accumulation function <m>A(t)</m> out of a function <m>f(t)</m>,
then we in fact have created an antiderivatitve for <m>f(t)</m>:
<me> A(t) = \ccmint{t_0}{t}{f(w)}{dw} \qquad\implies\qquad A'(t) = f(t) </me>.
(Here we are using <m>w</m> as the variable of integration because we are about to use the variable <m>u</m> for another purpose.)
</p>

<p>
What if we repeat the above for a derivative function?
Suppose <m>u(t)</m> is a differentiable function.
Then
<me> A(t) = \ccmint{t_0}{t}{u'(w)}{dw} \qquad\implies\qquad A'(t) = u'(t) </me>.
We know that two functions that have the same derivative must be vertical shifts of one another
(<xref ref="fact-fund-thm-antideriv-v-shifts" />),
so
<me> A(t) = u(t) + C </me>
for some constant <m>C</m>.
</p>

<p>
Let's analyze this using Riemann sums.
We have <me> \ccmint{t_0}{t}{u'(w)}{dw} \approx \sum_{k=1}^n u'(w_k^\ast) \change{w} </me>.
At each sample point <m>w_k^\ast</m>,
we can also approximate the derivative value by an average rate value over the same subdomain of width <m>dw</m> from which <m>w_k^\ast</m> was taken:
<me> u'(w_k^\ast) = \funceval{\dd{u}{w}}{w = w_k^\ast} \approx \slope{u}{w} </me>,
where <me> \slope{u}{w} = \frac{u(w_k) - u(w_{k-1})}{\change{w}} </me>.
This gives us
<md>
	<mrow> \ccmint{t_0}{t}{u'(w)}{dw} \amp \approx \sum_{k=1}^n u'(w_k^\ast) \change{w} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp \approx \sum_{k=1}^n \frac{\change{u}}{\cancel{\change{w}}} \, \cancel{\change{w}} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \sum_{k=1}^n \change{u} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \sum_{k=1}^n 1 \cdot \change{u} </mrow>
</md>.
This looks like a Riemann sum,
but where <m>u</m> is the <em>independent</em> variable instead of a dependent variable,
and the function used is just the constant function <m>1</m>:
<me> \sum_{k=1}^n 1 \cdot \change{u} \approx \ccmint{t_0}{t}{1}{u} </me>.
Since <m>u(t)</m> is assumed to be differentiable,
we may make <m>\change{u}</m> arbitrarily small by taking <m>\change{w}</m> sufficiently small,
so all of the approximations above can be made arbitrarily good:
<me> \ccmint{t_0}{t}{\dd{u}{w}}{w} = \ccmint{t_0}{t}{1}{u} </me>.
Normally, we don't bother to write the integrand <m>1</m> inside the second integral:
<me> \ccmint{t_0}{t}{\dd{u}{w}}{w} = \ccmint{t_0}{t}{}{u} </me>.
Choosing <m>u</m> as an antiderivative of <m>1</m> relative to the independent variable <m>u</m>,
we apply <xref ref="pattern-fund-thm-def-int-by-antideriv" /> to get
<md>
	<mrow> \ccmint{t_0}{t}{\dd{u}{w}}{w} \amp = \ccmint{t_0}{t}{}{u} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \funceval{u}{t} - \funceval{u}{t = t_0} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = u(t) - u(t_0) </mrow>
</md>
which is a vertical shift of <m>u(t)</m> as expected from our initial analysis above.
</p>
-->

<p>
<xref ref="pattern-fund-thm-def-int-by-antideriv" /> tells us that we may use an antiderivative to compute an integral:
<me> \ccmint{a}{b}{q(t)}{t} = Q(b) - Q(a) </me>
if <m>Q'(t) = q(t)</m>.
What if we apply the above to an integral of a derivative?
A function is an antiderivative of its own derivative,
so we have
<me> \ccmint{a}{b}{q'(t)}{t} = q(b) - q(a) </me>.
Since <m>q'(t)</m> is the rate of accumulation of the quantity <m>q(t)</m>,
this equality is stating the obvious:
accumulation is equal to accumulation.
</p>

<p>
In differential notation,
we could write
<md><mrow xml:id="equation-substitution-integral-of-deriv" tag="star">
	\ccmint{a}{b}{\dqdt}{t} = q(b) - q(a)
</mrow></md>.
Recall that this integral is a sum of small
<me> \text{accumulation} = \text{rate} \times \text{duration} </me>
calculations over tiny time intervals of duration <m>dt</m>.
But also, <m>dq/dt</m> is essentially an average rate calculation over a short time interval of duration <m>dt</m>.
If we assume that these two calculations are aligned to use the same <m>dt</m> <q>value</q>,
we could write <me> \dqdt \, dt = dq </me>,
and so
<md><mrow xml:id="equation-substitution-convert-integral-of-deriv" tag="dstar">
	\ccmint{a}{b}{\dqdt}{t} = \ccmint{q(a)}{q(b)}{}{q}
</mrow></md>.
Notice that we have changed the bounds of integration to reflect the fact that in our second integral,
<m>q</m> is now being considered as the <em>independent</em> variable instead of the dependent one.
Finally,
we apply <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props-constant" text="type-local">Property</xref>
of <xref ref="pattern-integ-definite-props" />
to this new integral to obtain
<md>
	<mrow> \ccmint{a}{b}{\dqdt}{t} \amp = \ccmint{q(a)}{q(b)}{}{q} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{q(a)}{q(b)}{1}{q} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = 1 \cdot \bbrac{q(b) - q(a)} </mrow>
	<mrow> \amp = q(b) - q(a) </mrow>
</md>,
just as in <xref ref="equation-substitution-integral-of-deriv" />.
</p>

<aside><title>Note</title><p>
	We could make this discussion more precise by considering an actual Riemann sum involving <m>\change{q}</m> and <m>\change{t}</m>,
	but we won't purse that here.
</p></aside>

<example>
	<title>Integrating a derivative</title>
	<p>
	Consider <m>q(t) = \sin(t)</m>,
	so that <m>q'(t) = \cos(t)</m>.
	Then
	<me> dq = \dqdt \, dt = \cos(t) dt </me>,
	so we can compute
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmint{-\pi/2}{\pi/2}{\cos(t)}{t} \amp = \ccmint{\sin(-\pi/2)}{\sin(\pi/2)}{}{q} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{\sin(-\pi/2)}{\sin(\pi/2)}{}{q} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{-1}{1}{}{q} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 1 - (-1) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 2 </mrow>
	</md>,
	which agrees with the many previous computations of this accumulation that we have made before.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
What if we apply all of the above to a derivative that has been calculated using the chain rule?
Suppose <m>q</m> is a function of <m>u</m> and <m>u</m> is a function of <m>t</m>.
Then ultimately <m>q</m> is a function of <m>t</m>,
and the <xref ref="pattern-chain-differential-version" text="title" /> says that
<me> \dqdt = \dqdu \cdot \dudt </me>.
If we are computing an integral
<me> \ccmint{a}{b}{\dqdt}{t} </me>,
we would need to know <m>q(t)</m> in order to use an analysis like that in <xref ref="equation-substitution-convert-integral-of-deriv" />.
So instead, we will use <m>u</m> as an <em>intermediate</em> variable:
<me> \dqdt \, dt = \dqdu \cdot \dudt \, dt = \dqdu \, du </me>,
giving us
<me> \ccmint{a}{b}{\dqdt}{t} = \ccmint{u(a)}{u(b)}{\dqdu}{u} </me>.
The hope is that this second integral is either something for which we already have a formula,
or for which it is simpler to guess an antiderivative.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-substitution-integral-of-chain">
	<title>Integrating the Chain Rule</title>
	<p>
	Consider <m>q(t) = \sqrt{t^2 + 1}</m>.
	In <xref ref="example-chain-radical" /> we used the substitution <m>u = t^2 + 1</m> to compute
	<me> q'(t) = \frac{t}{\sqrt{t^2 + 1}} = \frac{2 t}{2 \sqrt{t^2 + 1}} </me>,
	where <m>du/dt = 2 t</m>.
	Let's pretend we don't know the formula for <m>q(t)</m> and work in reverse.
	We can use <m>u</m> to compute
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\ccmint{2}{3}{\frac{t}{\sqrt{t^2 + 1}}}{t}
			\amp = \ccmint{2}{3}{\frac{2 t}{2 \sqrt{t^2 + 1}}}{t}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{2}{3}{\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{t^2 + 1}} \cdot (2 t)}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{2}{3}{\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{t^2 + 1}} \cdot \dudt}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{5}{10}{\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{u}}}{u}                  </mrow>
	</md>,
	where we have adjusted the bounds of integration to
	<md>
		<mrow> u(2) \amp = 2^2 + 1 \amp u(3) \amp = 3^2 + 1 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 5 \amp \amp = 9 </mrow>
	</md>
	when we converted to an integral in terms of <m>u</m>.
	This new integral is one we know how to deal with:
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\ccmint{2}{3}{\frac{t}{\sqrt{t^2 + 1}}}{t}
			\amp = \ccmint{5}{10}{\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{u}}}{u}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{2} \ccmint{5}{10}{u^{-1/2}}{u} </mrow>
	</md>
	Using antiderivative <me> U(t) = \frac{u^{1/2}}{1/2} </me>,
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\ccmint{2}{3}{\frac{t}{\sqrt{t^2 + 1}}}{t}
			\amp = \frac{1}{2} \ccmint{5}{10}{u^{-1/2}}{u}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \cancel{\frac{1}{2}} \left( \frac{{10}^{1/2}}{\cancel{1/2}} - \frac{5^{1/2}}{\cancel{1/2}} \right) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \sqrt{10} - \sqrt{5} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Remembering that we actually <em>do</em> know <m>q(t)</m>,
	notice that this result is the same as computing
	<me> \ccmint{2}{3}{\dqdt}{t} = q(3) - q(2) </me>.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section>
<title>Method of substitution</title>

<p>
In general,
it is difficult to recognize an integrand as a derivative function that is the result of a chain rule.
Even in <xref ref="example-substitution-integral-of-chain" />,
we had to go backwards one step from the final result of <xref ref="example-chain-radical" /> by reintroducing the <m>2</m> in both numerator and denominator in order to make it work.
So we create a slightly more general procedure that can be tried when we merely <em>suspect</em> that we have such an integrand that might be the result of a chain rule.
</p>

<algorithm xml:id="procedure-substitution">
	<title>Method of substitution</title>
	<p>
	If <m>f(t)</m> is a function that can be expressed as <me> f(t) = g(t) \, \dudt </me>,
	where <m>g(t)</m> can be converted into a function of <m>u</m> alone by substituting <m>u = u(t)</m>,
	then <me> \ccmint{a}{b}{f(t)}{t} = \ccmint{u(a)}{u(b)}{g(u)}{u} </me>.
	</p>
</algorithm>

<remark>
	<title>Method of substitution is structured <q>trial-and-error</q></title>
	<p>
	When we try this method,
	usually we guess at <m>u</m> first and tweak <m>g</m> to match.
	But it is often not obvious what <m>u</m> to try <mdash />
	sometimes we try some version of <m>u</m> and it leads to a dead end.
	In that case,
	we either try a different substitution by choosing a different <m>u</m>,
	or we try a different method all together.
	No matter what we try,
	our strategy when using substitution is to
	<alert>
		recognize the integrand as a product of two functions,
		where the second is related to the derivative of some <q>part</q> of the first
	</alert>.
	</p>
</remark>

<example>
	<title>Integral of a horizontal scaling</title>
	<p>
	For <me> \ccmint{0}{\pi/10}{\cos(5 t)}{t} </me>,
	consider <m>u = 5 t</m> with <m>du/dt = 5</m>.
	Since our integrand doesn't involve a multiple of <m>5</m> <em>outside</em> of the cosine function,
	we need to introduce one:
	<me> \cos(t) = \frac{\cos(5 t)}{5} \cdot 5 = \frac{\cos(5 t)}{5} \cdot \dudt </me>.
	So our <m>g(t)</m> is <me> g(t) = \frac{\cos(5 t)}{5} \qquad\implies\qquad g(u) = \frac{\cos(u)}{5} </me>,
	and our new bounds of integration are
	<md>
		<mrow> u(0) \amp = 5 \cdot 0 \amp u(\pi/10) \amp = 5 \cdot \pi/10 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 0 \amp \amp = \pi/2 </mrow>
	</md>
	and we can calculate
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmint{0}{\pi/10}{\cos(5 t)}{t} \amp = \ccmint{0}{\pi/2}{\frac{\cos(u)}{5}}{u} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{5} \ccmint{0}{\pi/2}{\cos(u)}{u} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{5} \bbrac{\sin(\pi/2) - \sin(0)} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{5} (1 - 0) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{5} </mrow>
	</md>,
	where we have used the antiderivative <m>\sin(u)</m> for <m>\cos(u)</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-substitution-hshift">
	<title>Integral of a horizontal shift</title>
	<p>
	For <me> \ccmint{0}{e^3 - 1}{\frac{1}{t + 1}}{t} </me>,
	we could probably guess an antiderivative involving a logarithm.
	But we can also be more systematic using substitution.
	Using
	<me> u = t + 1 \qquad\implies\qquad \dudt = 1 </me>
	and
	<md>
		<mrow> u(0) \amp = 0 + 1 \amp u(e^3 - 1) \amp = (e^3 - 1) + 1 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 1 \amp \amp = e^3 </mrow>
	</md>
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmint{0}{e^3 - 1}{\frac{1}{t + 1}}{t} \amp = \ccmint{0}{e^3 - 1}{\frac{du/dt}{t + 1}}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{1}{e^3}{\frac{1}{u}}{u} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Using the antiderivative <m>\ln\abs{u}</m> for <m>1/u</m>,
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmint{0}{e^3 - 1}{\frac{1}{t + 1}}{t} \amp = \ln\abs{e^3} - \ln\abs{1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 3 - 0 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 3 </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Another trig example</title>
	<p>
	For <me> \ccmint{0}{\pi/2}{\cos(t) \sin^2(t)}{t} </me>,
	we recognize that <m>\cos(t)</m> is the derivative of <m>\sin(t)</m>,
	so if we substitute
	<md><mrow> u \amp = \sin(t) \amp \dudt \amp = \cos(t) </mrow></md>
	and
	<md><mrow> u(0) \amp = 0 \amp u(\pi/2) = 1 </mrow></md>
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\ccmint{0}{\pi/2}{\cos(t) \sin^2(t)}{t}
			\amp = \ccmint{0}{\pi/2}{{\bbrac{\sin(t)}}^2 \dudt}{t}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmint{0}{1}{u^2}{u} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1^3}{3} - \frac{0^3}{3} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{3} </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>
</example>

<p> We can also use substitution to compute indefinite integrals. </p>

<example>
	<title>Substitution in an indefinite integral</title>
	<p>
	For <me> \ccmiint{t e^{t^2}}{t} </me> we recognize <m>d(t^2)/dt = 2 t</m>,
	so let's try substituting <m>u = t^2</m>.
	As with a previous example,
	the factor of <m>2</m> in <m>du/dt</m> is missing in our integrand,
	so we must artificially introduce it.
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{t e^{t^2}}{t} \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{e^{t^2}}{2} \cdot (2 t)}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{e^{t^2}}{2} \cdot \dudt }{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{e^u}{2}}{u} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{e^u}{2} + C </mrow>
	</md>.
	However,
	we weren't interested in the antidervivatives of <m>g(u) = e^u/2</m>,
	we wanted the antiderivatives of <m>f(t) = t e^{t^2}</m>.
	We need to substitute back in for <m>u</m>:
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{t e^{t^2}}{t} \amp = \frac{e^u}{2} + C </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{e^{t^2}}{2} + C </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>
</example>

<p> Sometimes there are multiple choices for the substitution. </p>

<example xml:id="example-substitution-two-choices">
	<title>Choosing the substitution</title>
	<p>
	For <me> \ccmiint{\sin(t) \cos(t)}{t} </me>,
	each of the two factors in the integrand is related to the derivative of the other.
	Let's choose <m>u = \sin(t)</m> so that <m>du/dt = \cos(t)</m>.
	Then,
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{\sin(t) \cos(t)}{t} \amp = \ccmiint{\sin(t) \cdot \dudt}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmiint{u}{u} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{u^2}{2} + C </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{\sin^2(t)}{2} + C </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise>
	<title>Choosing a different substitution</title>
	<p>
	Repeat <xref ref="example-substitution-two-choices" />,
	but this time choose <m>u = \cos(t)</m>.
	You will arrive at a seemingly different answer,
	but <xref ref="fact-fund-thm-antideriv-v-shifts" /> says that your result should be a vertical shift of the result computed in <xref ref="example-substitution-two-choices" />.
	Determine how.
	</p>
</exercise>

<p>
Somewhat similar to <xref ref="example-substitution-hshift" />,
we can sometimes use substitution to <q>shift</q> a complicated expression to another place in the integrand.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Shifting a sum from the denominator to the numerator</title>
	<p>
	For <me> \ccmiint{\frac{t^5}{t^2 + 1}}{t} </me>,
	the integrand would be easier to deal with if there wasn't a plus sign in the denominator.
	So let's try substituting <m>u = t^2 + 1</m>.
	Since <m>du/dt = 2 t</m>,
	we first reorganize the integrand,
	artificially introducing that factor of <m>2</m>.
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{\frac{t^5}{t^2 + 1}}{t} \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{ 2 t \cdot t^4 }{2 (t^2 + 1)}}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{t^4}{2 (t^2 + 1)} \cdot (2 t)}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{t^4}{2 (t^2 + 1)} \cdot \dudt}{t} </mrow>
	</md>.
	What about that numerator of <m>t^4</m>?
	Luckily, it can be expressed as a function of <m>u</m>:
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> t^2 + 1 = u </mrow>
		<mrow> t^2 = u - 1 </mrow>
		<mrow> t^4 = (u - 1)^2 </mrow>
	</md>.
	So
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{\frac{t^5}{t^2 + 1}}{t} \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{t^4}{2 (t^2 + 1)} \cdot \dudt}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{(u - 1)^2}{2 u}}{u} </mrow>
	</md>.
	Now that we have shifted the sum in the original denominator to be a difference in the numerator,
	we can manipulate the integrand algebraically before integrating:
	<md>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{\frac{t^5}{t^2 + 1}}{t} \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{(u - 1)^2}{2 u}}{u}  </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{u^2 - 2 u + 1}{2 u}}{u}                               </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \ccmiint{\frac{u}{2} - 1 + \frac{1}{2 u}}{u}                         </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{u^2}{4} - u + \frac{1}{2} \ln\abs{u} + C                       </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{(t^2 + 1)^2}{4} - (t^2 + 1) + \frac{1}{2} \ln\abs{t^2 + 1} + C </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-substitution-separable-DE">
<title>Separable rate equations</title>

<p>
Recall that a rate equation relates a quantity to its rate of variation.
Our goal in solving a rate equation is to relate the quantity directly to the independent variable.
Since a rate of variation is a derivative function,
ultimately solving a rate equation involves recognizing and reversing the differentiation.
When we can <q>separate</q> the variables involved in a rate function to either side of a rate equation,
on one side we can reverse the differentiation by reversing the chain rule.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-substitution-first-separable">
	<title>A first example</title>

	<p>
	Consider the rate equation <me> r(t) = \frac{t^2 + 1}{q(t) + 1} </me>.
	Let's simply write <m>q</m> instead of <m>q(t)</m>.
	But let's also replace <m>r(t)</m> with <m>dq/dt</m>,
	since <m>dq/dt</m> is the rate of variation of <m>q</m>.
	Finally, we'll also do a little algebraic rearrangement.
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow>                  r(t) = \frac{t^2 + 1}{q(t) + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow>                 \dqdt = \frac{t^2 + 1}{q + 1}                </mrow>
		<mrow>         (q + 1) \dqdt = t^2 + 1                              </mrow>
		<mrow> q \cdot \dqdt + \dqdt = t^2 + 1                              </mrow>
	</md>.
	The first term on the left now looks the type of result we would obtain when applying the chain rule during an implicit differentiation computation.
	In particular,
	<md>
		<mrow> \opddt \left( \frac{q^2}{2} \right) \amp = \frac{1}{2} \ddq{(q^2)} \dqdt </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{\cancel{2}} (\cancel{2} q) \dqdt </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = q \, \dqdt </mrow>
	</md>
	So,
	in effect we can <q>factor</q> the <m>d/dt</m> operator out of the left-hand side of the last equation above:
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> q \cdot \dqdt + \dqdt = t^2 + 1  </mrow>
		<mrow> \implies \qquad \opddt \left( \frac{q^2}{2} + q \right) = t^2 + 1  </mrow>
	</md>.
	So now we explicitly have the left-hand side as a derivative calculation.
	Since the two sides are equal,
	let's make them appear more the same by also interpreting the right-hand side as the result of a derivative calculation.
	Since
	<me> \opddt \, \left( \frac{t^3}{3} + t \right) = t^2 + 1 </me>,
	we can write
	<me> \opddt \left( \frac{q^2}{2} + q \right) = \opddt \, \left( \frac{t^3}{3} + t \right) </me>.
	This now says that the functions
	<md><mrow> \frac{q^2}{2} \amp + q \amp \frac{t^3}{3} \amp + t </mrow></md>
	have the same derivative.
	From <xref ref="fact-fund-thm-antideriv-v-shifts" />,
	we know that this means that they must be vertical shifts of each other:
	<me> \frac{q^2}{2} + q = \frac{t^3}{3} + t + C </me>.
	</p>

	<p>
	So far, we have obtained an implicit expression relating <m>q</m> to <m>t</m>.
	It's not always possible to isolate <m>q</m>,
	but in this case we can use the <xref ref="pattern-poly-quadratic-formula" text="title" />
	to obtain a <q>lower</q> and an <q>upper</q> solution:
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> \frac{q^2}{2} + q = \frac{t^3}{3} + t + C</mrow>
		<mrow> 3 q^2 + 6 q = 2 t^3 + 6 t + C </mrow>
		<mrow> 3 q^2 + 6 q - (2 t^3 + 6 t + C) = 0 </mrow>
	</md>.
	<md>
		<mrow>
			q(t) \amp = \frac{-6 - \sqrt{36 - 12 (2 t^3 + 6 t + C)}}{6}
			\amp
			q(t) \amp = \frac{-6 + \sqrt{36 + 12 (2 t^3 + 6 t + C)}}{6}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = -1 - \sqrt{1 - 2 t^3 / 3 - 2 t + C}
			\amp
			\amp = -1 + \sqrt{1 - 2 t^3 / 3 - 2 t + C}
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = -1 - \sqrt{C - 2 t^3 / 3 - 2 t}
			\amp
			\amp = -1 + \sqrt{C - 2 t^3 / 3 - 2 t}
		</mrow>
	</md>.
	Notice when we perform algebraic operations involving <m>C</m>,
	we haven't bothered to alter it,
	since if <m>C</m> is an arbitrary value,
	then so is <m>6 C</m>, for example.
	In fact,
	under the square root sign we have even absorbed the extra <m>1</m> into the constant <m>C</m>,
	since <m>1 + C</m> is just as arbitrary as <m>C</m> itself.
	</p>

	<p>
	Our two classes of solutions both involve the parameter <m>C</m>,
	which would have to be determined using a known or desired initial value.
	For example, if we wanted a solution of the <q>upper</q> type that satisfied <m>q(0) = 4</m>,
	we could solve for <m>C</m>:
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> 4 = -1 + \sqrt{C - 2 0^3 / 3 - 2 \cdot 0} </mrow>
		<mrow> 5 = \sqrt{C} </mrow>
		<mrow> 25 = C </mrow>
	</md>.
	So the solution that satisfies <m>q(0) = 4</m> is
	<me> q(t) = -1 + \sqrt{25 - 2 t^3 / 3 - 2 t} </me>.
	</p>

</example>

<definition xml:id="definition-substitution-separable-DE">
	<title>Separable rate equation</title>
	<p>
	A rate equation that can be expressed in the form
	<me> m(q) \cdot \dqdt = n(t) </me>
	for some functions <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> is called <term>separable</term>.
	</p>
</definition>

<p>
Ultimately,
the problem in <xref ref="example-substitution-first-separable" /> was solved by reversing differentiation,
also known as <em>antidifferentiating</em>.
</p>

<algorithm xml:id="procedure-substitution-solve-separable">
	<title>Solving a separable rate equation</title>
	<p>
	To solve <me> m(q) \cdot \dqdt = n(t) </me>,
	integrate both sides:
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> m(q) \cdot \dqdt = n(t) </mrow>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{m(q) \cdot \dqdt}{t} = \ccmiint{n(t)}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{m(q)}{q} = \ccmiint{n(t)}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> M(q) = N(t) + C </mrow>
	</md>,
	where <m>M(q)</m> is an antiderivative for <m>m(q)</m>
	(with respect to <m>q</m>)
	and <m>N(t)</m> is an antiderivative for <m>n(t)</m>
	(with respect to <m>t</m>).
	Notice that we have introduced an arbitrary constant of integration on one side only.
	</p>
</algorithm>

<example>
	<title>Solving exponential decay</title>

	<p>
	Let's once again revisit <xref ref="example-models-radioactive-decay" />,
	which involved the rate equation
	<me> \frac{r(t)}{q(t)} = - k </me>.
	In <xref ref="example-deriv-solution-to-proportional-rate-equation" />
	we verified that an horizontally-transformed exponential function can be a solution to this type of rate equation.
	Now we'll solve this equation to verify that exponential functions are the <em>only</em> possible solutions.
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> \frac{1}{q} \cdot \dqdt = -k </mrow>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{\frac{1}{q} \cdot \dqdt}{t} = \ccmiint{-k}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{\frac{1}{q}}{q} = \ccmiint{-k}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \ln\abs{q} = -k t + C </mrow>
	</md>.
	To isolate <m>q</m>,
	we undo the logarithm by taking the exponential of each side.
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> \exp\bbrac{\ln\abs{q}} = e^{-k t + C} </mrow>
		<mrow> \abs{q} = e^C \cdot e^{-k t}  </mrow>
	</md>.
	Now, the exponentials on the left are always positive,
	but the <m>q</m> inside the absolute value brackets could be positive or negative,
	so again we really have a <q>lower</q> and <q>upper</q> solution
	<md><mrow> q \amp = e^C \cdot e^{-k t} \amp q \amp = - e^C \cdot e^{-k t} </mrow></md>
	However, as <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant,
	together <m>\pm e^C</m> can take on any non-zero value,
	so we unify these two solutions by letting <m>A</m> represent either of <m>\pm e^C</m>:
	<me> q(t) = A e^{-k t} </me>.
	Notice that <m>A</m> represents the initial value <m>q(0)</m>,
	since <m>e^0 = 1</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	One last thing to consider is that if <m>A = \pm e^C</m>,
	then <m>A = 0</m> is not possible.
	And that's good,
	because <m>q = 0</m> would not work in
	<me> \frac{r(t)}{q(t)} = - k </me>.
	However,
	if we rearrange this to
	<me> r(t) = - k q(t) </me>,
	then <m>q(t) = 0</m> would in fact be a solution,
	since then <m>q'(t) = 0</m> also,
	so
	<md>
		<mrow> \text{LHS} \amp = r(t) \amp \text{RHS} \amp = -k q(t) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = q'(t) \amp \text{RHS} \amp = -k \cdot 0 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 0 \amp \text{RHS} \amp = 0 </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>

</example>

<p> Let's record the pattern of the solution to the previous example. </p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-substitution-proportional-rate">
	<title>Solution to proportional rate equation</title>
	<p>
	If <m>q(t)</m> is a varying quantity so that its rate of variation <m>r(t)</m> is always proportional to the amount <m>q(t)</m> according to the rate equation
	<me> r(t) = k q(t) </me>,
	then <m>q(t)</m> is the exponential function <me> q(t) = q_0 e^{k t} </me>,
	where <m>q_0 = q(0)</m> is the initial quantity.
	</p>
</identity>

<p>
As one last example,
let's return to the rate equation from <xref ref="example-models-general-solution" />.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-substitution-solve-previous-example">

	<p>
	In <xref ref="example-models-general-solution" /> we considered the rate equation
	<me> r(t) = \frac{q(t) \cdot \bbrac{1 - q(t)}}{t + 1} </me>.
	This is somewhat similar to <xref ref="example-substitution-first-separable" />,
	except this time the solution will involve logarithms,
	because after separating variables we will have reciprocal functions on both sides.
	<me> \frac{1}{q (1 - q)} \cdot \dqdt = \frac{1}{t + 1} </me>.
	Because of the product in the denominator,
	the left-hand side looks like something you get after obtaining a common denominator.
	In fact, combining <me> \frac{1}{q} + \frac{1}{1 - q} </me>
	into a single fraction leads to our left-hand side above (without the <m>dq/dt</m>).
	<md>
		<mrow> \left(\frac{1}{q} + \frac{1}{1 - q}\right) \cdot \dqdt = \frac{1}{t + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \ccmiint{\frac{1}{q} + \frac{1}{1 - q}}{q} = \ccmiint{\frac{1}{t + 1}}{t} </mrow>
	</md>
	For each of the right-hand side and the second term on the left-hand side,
	we could perform a substitution similarly to <xref ref="example-substitution-hshift" />,
	but we can probably just guess-and-check these antiderivatives using the logarithm:
	<me> \ln\abs{q} - \ln\abs{1 - q} = \ln\abs{t + 1} + C </me>,
	where the original addition on the left has turned into subtraction to correct the extra negative we would get from the chain rule if we differentiated <m>\ln\abs{1 - q}</m> to check our answer.
	</p>

	<p>
	Finally,
	we would like to solve for <m>q</m> if possible.
	We use the properties of the logarithm to combine the two terms on the left,
	and then apply the exponential function to <q>undo</q> the logarithm.
	<md alignment="gather">
		<mrow> \ln\abs{\frac{q}{1 - q}} = \ln\abs{t + 1} + C </mrow>
		<mrow> \exp\left(\ln\abs{\frac{q}{1 - q}}\right) = \exp\bbrac{\ln\abs{t + 1} + C} </mrow>
		<mrow> \abs{\frac{q}{1 - q}} = \exp\bbrac{\ln\abs{t + 1}} \cdot e^C </mrow>
		<mrow> \abs{\frac{q}{1 - q}} = e^C \abs{t + 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \frac{q}{1 - q} = \pm e^C (t + 1) </mrow>
	</md>
	Replace <m>\pm e^C</m> with arbitrary <m>A</m>:
	<md alignment ="gather">
		<mrow> q = A (t + 1)(1 - q) </mrow>
		<mrow> q = A (t + 1) - A (t + 1) q </mrow>
		<mrow> q +  A (t + 1) q = A (t + 1) </mrow>
		<mrow> \bbrac{ 1 +  A (t + 1) } q = A (t + 1) </mrow>
		<mrow> q(t) = \frac{A (t + 1)}{ 1 +  A (t + 1) } </mrow>
	</md>,
	where <m>A</m> is an arbitrary constant.
	This general solution appears different from the one previously provided in <xref ref="example-models-general-solution" />,
	but this solution can be converted into that solution by substituting <me> A = \frac{c}{1 -c} </me>,
	where <m>c</m> also represents an arbitrary constant.
	</p>

</example>

<exercise><p>
	In <xref ref="example-substitution-solve-previous-example" />,
	letting <m>A</m> represent <m>\pm e^C</m> implies that <m>A</m> cannot be zero,
	since an exponential is never <m>0</m>.
	Verify that setting <m>A = 0</m> in the final formula for <m>q(t)</m> actually does lead to a valid particular solution,
	by substituting that version of <m>q(t)</m> (and its derivative) into the left-hand and right-hand sides of the original rate equation.
</p></exercise>


</section>

